<HEADLINE>
<P>
HINTS FROM HELOISE: CORN SYRUP AS A HONEY SUBSTITUTE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DEAR HELOISE: I was getting ready to bake a dessert when I realized I didn't 
have the honey that the recipe called for. It happened that a friend was 
visiting and she told me I could substitute corn syrup for honey or granulated 
sugar. I didn't argue with her but it didn't seem right. Can you actually make 
this substitution? 
</P>
<P>
 -- CONFUSED BAKER, Casper, Wyo. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR CONFUSED: Generally, corn syrup can be substituted for honey in most 
recipes. When using corn syrup, remember that it isn't as sweet as the honey 
and that the dessert in turn will not be as sweet. 
</P>
<P>
When substitutions are made, the texture and flavor of recipes will be slightly 
altered. 
</P>
<P>
You cannot substitute corn syrup for granulated sugar. With one being a liquid 
and the other a dry ingredient, it's difficult to adjust the ingredients in the 
recipe so that it would come out correctly. 
</P>
<P>
 -- HELOISE 
</P>
<P>
DEAR HELOISE: I love popcorn and pop it in the evenings to take to work the 
next day to snack on. I put it in a large resealable plastic bag. I cut a small 
hole in the corner of the bag, give the bag a good shake and all the unpopped 
kernels come out of the hole. 
</P>
<P>
Now when I grab a handful of popcorn I don't worry about the loose kernels 
breaking one of my teeth. 
</P>
<P>
 -- OLIVIA, Red Bank, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR READERS: I have received many requests for the ingredients I use in my 
coffee ole, so I thought I would pass it along. 
</P>
<P>
Make a regular cup of coffee, add a little extra skim milk and a tablespoon of 
powdered skim milk. Add sugar (I use artificial sweetener) to taste. Put this 
mixture in the blender and blend until it is foamy. 
</P>
<P>
Make sure that the coffee mug is microwaveable and place it in the microwave on 
Warm for just a couple of seconds. This gives the coffee a wonderful new taste. 
</P>
<P>
 -- HELOISE 
</P>
<P>
DEAR HELOISE: At one time I read a hint that said you could ripen avocados in 
the microwave. Is this possible? 
</P>
<P>
 -- EVELYN, Cedar Rapids, Iowa 
</P>
<P>
DEAR EVELYN: The hint that we printed said to poke several holes in an avocado 
and place it in the microwave on MEDIUM heat (50%) for about two minutes. 
</P>
<P>
However, after further testing of this hint, we found it didn't work every 
time. It did help some of the avocados, while others were soft but still tasted 
unripe. You might want to give it a try to see how your avocado comes out. 
</P>
<P>
You can also put an unripe avocado in a brown paper bag and fold over the top 
to close and put in a warm place. (The top of the refrigerator is good.) It 
should be ripe in two to three days. 
</P>
<P>
 -- HELOISE 
</P>
<P>
DEAR HELOISE: During hectic mornings, everything used to stop while my husband 
and I searched for the correct change for our child's lunch, bus or milk money. 
</P>
<P>
Now we keep a bowl by the door. When we have change we drop it in the bowl. 
This way the children have change for whatever reason and mornings are a little 
bit easier. 
</P>
<P>
 -- KATHY, Bangor, Me. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR HELOISE: Is there a substitute for powdered sugar? It seems that whenever 
I need some I never have it. I hate going to the grocery store for only one 
item. 
</P>
<P>
 -- JENNIE, El Paso, Tex. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR JENNIE: After speaking with our local home economist, the following is the 
substitution we found to work best. 
</P>
<P>
You will need one cup of granulated sugar and one tablespoon of cornstarch. 
Place this in a blender on high speed for several minutes. It will be powdery 
and ready for use. 
</P>
<P>
As with most substitutes, the consistency and texture of the dish may be 
altered slightly. 
</P>
<P>
 -- HELOISE 
</P>
<P>
DEAR HELOISE: I have seen several pet peeves in your column and thought I would 
share mine with you: when merchants affix difficult-to-remove price stickers 
directly to the merchandise or directly over the instructions on the 
merchandise. 
</P>
<P>
I spend hours trying to get these off, and it really burns me up. 
</P>
<P>
 -- READER, Chicago 
</P>
<P>
DEAR READER: This is one of my peeves too. I have this problem when I am 
looking at a package and want to read the ingredients or the calorie count and 
the sticker is covering it. 
</P>
<P>
 -- HELOISE 
</P>
<P>
 Send a time- or money-saving hint to Heloise, P.O. Box 795000, San Antonio, 
Tex. 78279. Letters will not be answered personally, but the best hints 
received will be used in the Hints From Heloise column. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
